Based on the provided documentation, it seems that deploying a workload on Google Cloud Pub/Sub involves creating a Pub/Sub function and configuring it to receive events from Pub/Sub. Here's a step-by-step guide based on the context:

1. Create a Terraform configuration file (`main.tf`) to define the required resources, including a service account and a random ID for bucket prefix.
```
resource "random_id" "bucket_prefix" {
  byte_length = 8
}
resource "google_service_account" "default" {
  account_id   = "test-gcf-sa"
  display_name = "Test Service Account"
}
```
[Source: gcp/Cloud Functions/Terraform Pub/Sub TutorialStay organized with collectionsSave and categorize content based on your preferences. > Preparing the application]

2. Define a Cloud Function that consumes events from Pub/Sub using the `functions_framework.cloud_event` function.
```go
func helloPubSub(ctx context.Context, e event.Event) error {
  var msg MessagePublishedData
  if err := e.DataAs(&msg); err != nil {
    return fmt.Errorf("event.DataAs: %w", err)
  }
  name := string(msg.Message.Data)
  // Automatically decoded from base64.
  if name == "" {
    name = "World"
  }
  log.Printf("Hello, %s!", name)
  return nil
}
```
[Source: gcp/Cloud Functions/Locally test your function > Cloud Pub/Sub event-driven function example > Go]

3. Use Terraform to deploy the Cloud Function and configure it to receive events from Pub/Sub.
```
resource "google_cloudfunctions_function" "pubsub" {
  name        = "hello-pubsub"
  runtime     = "go113"
  entry_point = "helloPubSub"
  source_url  = "https://github.com/terraform-google-modules/terraform-docs-samples.git"
}
```
[Source: gcp/Cloud Functions/Terraform Pub/Sub TutorialStay organized with collectionsSave and categorize content based on your preferences. > Preparing the application]

Note that this is a high-level overview, and you may need to modify the Terraform configuration and Cloud Function code to suit your specific requirements.

